documents.t: tip This documentation outlines everything there is to know about FPSMath. If you're new to FPSMath, we suggest you follow this guide by clicking "Next" at the bottom of the page when you're done reading!

For commands that accept input, you'll see keys with the following: <required> - parameters between <> must be included with the command [optional] - parameters between [] are optional parameters and may be excluded a | or | b - | means that you can use the parameters on either side of the symbol repeat... - means that you can provide multiple parameters as input These may be nested. Example: [parameter1 <parameter2\>] means that the input is optional, but if you provide parameter1 then parameter2 is required. [parameter...] means that input is optional, and that the input can be any number of parameters.

Converts Sensitivity to cm/rev Usage# /cm <sens> <game | yaw value> <cpi> Copy Supported Flags# -dp <output decimal places> Copy Examples# Anima04/07/2021 /cm 3 ow 1600 FPSMathBot04/07/2021 @Anima, 28.86 cm/rev Anima04/07/2021 /cm 2 0.022 800 -dp 8 FPSMathBot04/07/2021 @Anima, 25.97727273 cm/rev Aliases# cm/rev, cm/360 Copy

Converts Sensitivity to deg/mm Usage# /deg <sens> <game | yaw value> <cpi> Copy Supported Flags# -dp <output decimal places> Copy Examples# Anima04/07/2021 /deg 3 ow 1600 FPSMathBot04/07/2021 @Anima, 1.24724 deg/mm Anima04/07/2021 /deg 2 0.022 800 -dp 8 FPSMathBot04/07/2021 @Anima, 1.38582677 deg/mm Aliases# deg/mm Copy

Converts Sensitivity to mpi(mrad/inch) Usage# /mpi <sens> <game | yaw value> <cpi> Copy Supported Flags# -dp <output decimal places> Copy Examples# Anima04/07/2021 /mpi 3 ow 1600 FPSMathBot04/07/2021 @Anima, 1.24724 mpi Anima04/07/2021 /mpi 2 0.022 800 -dp 8 FPSMathBot04/07/2021 @Anima, 1.38582677 mpi Aliases# mrad, milliradian, mrad/inch, milliradian/inch Copy

Converts sensitivty to inch/rev(inch/360) Usage# /inch <sens> <game | yaw value> <cpi> Copy Supported Flags# -dp <output decimal places> Copy Examples# Anima04/07/2021 /inch 3 ow 1600 FPSMathBot04/07/2021 @Anima, 1.24724 inch/360 Anima04/07/2021 /inch 2 0.022 800 -dp 8 FPSMathBot04/07/2021 @Anima, 1.38582677 inch/360 Aliases# inch/360, inch/rev Copy

Converts different sensitivities from one game or yaw value to another Usage# /convert <sens> <input game | yaw> <output game | yaw> Copy Supported Flags# -dp <output decimal places> Copy Examples# Anima04/07/2021 /convert 6 wz 0.022 FPSMathBot04/07/2021 @Anima, 1.80000

Finds the true vertical and horizontal FOVs for certain aspect ratio that the game is being rendered at and game/FOV scaling method(FILM notation) To learn about FILM notation click here Usage# /fov <fov> <fov> <gamename | FILM notation> <aspect ratio> Copy Supported Flags# -dp <output decimal places> Copy Examples# Anima04/07/2021 /fov 90 4ML3 16:19 FPSMathBot04/07/2021 @Anima, Horizontal FOV: 64.551Vertical FOV: 73.740 Anima04/07/2021 /fov 103 ow 1920:1440 FPSMathBot04/07/2021 @Anima, Horizontal FOV: 103.000Vertical FOV: 56.631 Aliases# fov-scaling, film, fovscailing Copy

Focal Length Scales a desired sensitivity between 2 fov values of the same type/ game Usage# /focal <sens> <old fov> <new fov> Copy Supported Flags# -dp <output decimal places> Copy Examples# Anima04/07/2021 /focal 0.95 90 100 FPSMathBot04/07/2021 @Anima, 1.13217 Aliases# focal-scailing, visomotor, focalscailing Copy

Converts cm/rev(default), deg/mm, inch/rev, mpi or arcmin to a game sensitivity warning arcmin not implemented Usage# sens <cm/rev | deg/mm | inch/rev | mpi | arcmin> <game | yaw> <cpi> Copy Supported Flags# -cm // if the input value's unit is cm/rev it is the default and optional -deg // if the inpit value's unit is deg/mm -inch // if the inpit value's unit is inch/rev -mpi // if the inpit value's unit is mpi -arcmin // if the inpit value's unit is arcmin Copy Examples# Anima04/07/2021 /sens 28.5 quake 1600 FPSMathBot04/07/2021 @Anima, 0.91148 Aliases# sens-cm, sens-deg, sens-inch, senscm, sensdeg, sensinch, sensmpi, sens-mpi, sensarcmin, sens-arcmin Copy
tip Remember to use the bot prefix when running a command! You can also use @FPSMath instead of the server's prefix. Example @FPSMath help Below is a shortlist of all the bot commands.

Hint: You can click on a command to go to its full help entry. Command Description /cm Converts Sensitivity to cm/rev /deg Converts Sensitivity to deg/mm /mpi Converts Sensitivity to MPI /inch Converts Sensitivity to inch/rev /convert Converts Different Sensitivities from one game to another /fov Finds the true vertical and horizontal FOVs for certain aspect ratio and game/FOV scaling method(FILM notation) /focal Focal Length Scales a desired sens between 2 fov values of the same type /sens Converts cm/rev|deg/mm|MPI|inch/rev to a game sensitivity default cm/rev

Command Description /prefix Shows or sets the command prefix. /help Displays a list of available commands, or detailed information for a specified command. /games Displays the supported games for this bot /getobject Displays the object from the array associated for a game /info Displays the major information about this bot /cminfo Displays an explaination for what cm/rev (cm/360) is

Docusaurus supports the Markdown syntax and has some additional features.

Markdown documents can have associated metadata at the top called Front Matter: --- id: my-doc title: My document title description: My document description sidebar_label: My doc --- Markdown content Copy
Regular Markdown links are supported using url paths or relative file paths.

Markdown code blocks are supported with Syntax highlighting. ```jsx title="src/components/HelloDocusaurus.js" function HelloDocusaurus() { return (

Hello, Docusaurus!

) } ``` Copy src/components/HelloDocusaurus.js function HelloDocusaurus() { return

Hello, Docusaurus!

; } Copy

Docusaurus has a special syntax to create admonitions and callouts: :::tip My tip Use this awesome feature option ::: :::danger Take care This action is dangerous ::: Copy My tip Use this awesome feature option Take care This action is dangerous

Thanks to MDX, you can make your doc more interactive and use React components inside Markdown: export const Highlight = ({children, color}) => ( {children} ); Docusaurus green and Facebook blue are my favorite colors. Copy Docusaurus greenFacebook blue
